<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,1652,2037]" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">
For the identification of 
<taxonomicName box="[480,643,1687,1712]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Plastocorypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[480,643,1687,1712]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">Plastocorypha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (five species in OSF) not many characters are available. Our males have a dark orange red face (
<figureCitation box="[563,645,1724,1749]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1940,1962]" captionTargetBox="[205,1336,193,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[205,1337,193,1858]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 13. Habitus. A— Oxyaspis congensis, active, B— Oxyaspis congensis, nearly at rest, C— Zabalius apicalis inversus, D— Pantecphylus (P.) helleri, E— Batodromeus subulo, F— Lichenochrus congicus, G— Leproscirtus granulosus ♂, H— Leproscirtus granulosus ♀, I— Karniella crassicerca, J— Plastocorypha ituriana." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/250521/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">
Fig. 
<number box="[617,645,1724,1748]" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
J). Applying this character, the two 
<taxonomicName box="[1069,1233,1724,1749]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Plastocorypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1069,1233,1724,1749]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">Plastocorypha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms with black faces (
<emphasis box="[224,453,1760,1784]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">
<taxonomicName box="[224,335,1760,1784]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Lanistoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrifrons">nigrifrons</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName box="[342,453,1760,1784]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Lanistoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrifrons">nigrifrons</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[506,622,1759,1784]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">vandikana</emphasis>
) can be excluded. In these two forms, the tip of the fastigium is tapering, while it is blunt in 
<taxonomicName box="[376,500,1796,1821]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Plastocorypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevipes">
<emphasis box="[376,500,1796,1821]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">P. brevipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see OSF) and our animals. The remaining three forms have all dark orange red (“ferruginous”) faces and are all distributed in Central Africa— 
<taxonomicName authority="Rehn, 1914" authorityName="Rehn" authorityYear="1914" box="[891,1130,1831,1856]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Plastocorypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevipes">
<emphasis box="[891,985,1831,1856]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">brevipes</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Rehn" box="[996,1130,1831,1856]" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" refString="Rehn, J. A. G. (1914) Orthoptera. I. Mantidae, Phasmidae, Acrididae, Tettigoniidae und Gryllidae aus dem Zentral - Afrikanischen Gebiet, Uganda und dem Ituri - Becken des Kongos. Wissenschaftliche Ergebnisse der deutschen Zentral - Afrika Expedition, 1907 - 1908, Leipzig, 5 (Zool. 3 [1]), 1 - 223." type="journal article" year="1914">
Rehn, 
<number box="[1072,1130,1832,1856]" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" value="1914.0">1914</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Griffini 1909" authorityName="Griffini" authorityYear="1909" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Lanistoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="nigrifrons" variety="cabrai">
<emphasis box="[1146,1340,1831,1856]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">nigrifrons cabrai</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Griffini" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" refString="Griffini, A. (1909) Note sopra alcune Phasgonuridae del Congo. Annales de la Societe entomologique de Belgique, 53 (1908), 9 - 28." type="journal article" year="1909">
Griffini 
<number box="[151,207,1868,1892]" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" value="1909.0">1909</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[261,351,1869,1892]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Plastocorypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ituriana">
<emphasis box="[261,351,1869,1892]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">ituriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation author="Bolivar" box="[358,509,1868,1893]" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" refString="Bolivar, I. (1922) Orthopteres. In: Voyage de M. Le Baron Maurice de Rothschild en Ethiopie et en Afrique orientale anglaise 1904 - l 905). Animaux Articules, Paris. Imprimerie National 1, pp. 169 - 219, pls (10) 1 - (10) 4." type="journal article" year="1922">
Bolivar 
<number box="[449,509,1868,1892]" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" value="1922.0">1922</number>
</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[519,641,1868,1893]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Plastocorypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevipes">
<emphasis box="[519,641,1868,1893]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">P. brevipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has shorter hind femora than the other two and our specimens. Bolivar did not give any diagnosis when describing 
<taxonomicName box="[690,780,1905,1928]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Plastocorypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ituriana">
<emphasis box="[690,780,1905,1928]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">ituriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, only “voisine de vandikana” (=related to 
<emphasis box="[1303,1419,1903,1928]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">vandikana</emphasis>
). Although 
<emphasis box="[264,337,1941,1964]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">caprai</emphasis>
(we propose to treat it as species due to the difference in colour of the face) and 
<taxonomicName box="[1255,1346,1941,1964]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Plastocorypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ituriana">
<emphasis box="[1255,1346,1941,1964]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">ituriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be the same taxon, we will call our animals at the moment 
<taxonomicName box="[780,898,1977,2000]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Plastocorypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ituriana">
<emphasis box="[780,898,1977,2000]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">P. ituriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, since the 
<typeStatus box="[1020,1068,1977,2001]" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName authority="Mayumbe" authorityName="Mayumbe" box="[1197,1410,1976,2001]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Plastocorypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cabrai">
<emphasis box="[1197,1270,1976,2001]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="370">cabrai</emphasis>
(Mayumbe)
</taxonomicName>
is near the Atlantic Ocean.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,151,357]" pageId="28" pageNumber="371">
Song. The calling song (
<figureCitation box="[472,553,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="28.[151,250,746,768]" captionTargetBox="[164,1414,444,710]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[151,1436,411,724]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 17. Oscillogram of calling song of Plastocorypha ituriana (6 s sequence)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/250525/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="371">
Fig. 
<number box="[524,553,152,176]" pageId="28" pageNumber="371" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
) consisted of long echemes (ca. 
<number box="[918,932,152,176]" pageId="28" pageNumber="371" value="4.0">4</number>
s) with a syllable repetition rate of ca. 
<number box="[1368,1396,152,176]" pageId="28" pageNumber="371" value="40.0">40</number>
Hz (T= 
<number box="[199,227,188,212]" pageId="28" pageNumber="371" value="21.0">21</number>
ºC). In our nightly field recording, two males were imperfectly synchronizing, at the beginning or the end of the echeme the softer singing male could be heard (in 
<figureCitation box="[757,837,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1224,1246]" captionTargetBox="[340,1247,555,1202]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[340,1247,555,1202]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 16. A—Stridulatory file Leproscirtus granulosus (three-quarter view; articulation below); B—Right tegmen of Leproscirtus granulosus; C—Stridulatory file of Plastocorypha ituriana (articulation below). Scales 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/250524/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="371">
Fig. 
<number box="[809,837,223,248]" pageId="28" pageNumber="371" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
at the end). The echemes were separated by intervals of ca. 
<number box="[220,248,260,285]" pageId="28" pageNumber="371" value="25.0">25</number>
s.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,151,357]" pageId="28" pageNumber="371">
The stridulatory file (
<figureCitation box="[437,517,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1224,1246]" captionTargetBox="[340,1247,555,1202]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[340,1247,555,1202]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 16. A—Stridulatory file Leproscirtus granulosus (three-quarter view; articulation below); B—Right tegmen of Leproscirtus granulosus; C—Stridulatory file of Plastocorypha ituriana (articulation below). Scales 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/250524/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="371">
Fig. 
<number box="[489,517,295,320]" pageId="28" pageNumber="371" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
C) is similar to that figured in OSF for 
<taxonomicName box="[959,1080,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Plastocorypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="371" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevipes">
<emphasis box="[959,1080,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="371">P. brevipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In both species there is a small bulge near the proximal end.
</paragraph>
